[('Chersobius signatus', Chersobius signatus is the world's smallest species of tortoise (family Testudinidae). The species is commonly known as the speckled tortoise and also known locally as the speckled padloper and internationally as the speckled Cape tortoise. A member of the genus Chersobius, it is endemic to South Africa., ['https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/44/Homopus_signatus-Prague_Zoo.jpg', 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/70/Status_iucn3.1_EN.svg', 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/74/Red_Pencil_Icon.png', 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/ee/Speckled_Padloper_-_Homopus_Signatus_1.jpg', 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/4/4a/Commons-logo.svg', 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/9/95/Desert_tortoise_tds.jpg']), ('Chersobius boulengeri', Chersobius boulengeri, commonly known as the Karoo padloper or Boulenger's cape tortoise, is a species of tortoise in the family Testudinidae. The species is endemic to the Nama Karoo Region of South Africa., ['https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/70/Status_iucn3.1_EN.svg', 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/74/Red_Pencil_Icon.png', 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/8b/Karoo_Padloper_-_RSA.jpg', 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/9/95/Desert_tortoise_tds.jpg']), ('Chersobius signatus', Chersobius signatus is the world's smallest species of tortoise (family Testudinidae). The species is commonly known as the speckled tortoise and also known locally as the speckled padloper and internationally as the speckled Cape tortoise. A member of the genus Chersobius, it is endemic to South Africa., ['https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/44/Homopus_signatus-Prague_Zoo.jpg', 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/70/Status_iucn3.1_EN.svg', 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/74/Red_Pencil_Icon.png', 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/ee/Speckled_Padloper_-_Homopus_Signatus_1.jpg', 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/4/4a/Commons-logo.svg', 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/9/95/Desert_tortoise_tds.jpg']), ('Chersobius solus', 'Chersobius solus, commonly known as the Nama padloper or Berger\'s cape tortoise, is a species of tortoise in the Chersobius (padloper) genus. It is endemic to Namibia.\nThe species is threatened by traffic on roads, habitat destruction, and poaching for the pet trade. As the trade in collected Chersobius  species is strictly illegal and any captive specimens are systematically registered in noncommercial studbooks in South Africa and Namibia, any commercial sale of Chersobius tortoises is almost without exception strictly illegal. Another threat comes from introduced species, such as domestic dogs and pigs.The species does not generally survive well in captivity unless some effort is made to supply specimens with their natural food, that is, endemic plants from the Cape/Karoo regions.', ['https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/65/Turtleicon.png', 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/74/Red_Pencil_Icon.png', 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/83/Sitzungsberichte_%281910%29_%2814595713120%29.jpg', 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/dd/Status_iucn2.3_VU.svg', 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/9/95/Desert_tortoise_tds.jpg'])]